<span class="displaytext"><b>the (candidate last) vision vs. (PARTY NAME)' strategy of defeat &amp; retreat</b> <p align="center"> <b> <em>"he talked about his business strengths as well as focusing heavily on the need for better trade agreements, less corporate taxes and energy independence as ways to keep the american economy strong. (candidate last) said the country needs to understand that trade is good if it is done right."</em> </b> (john boyanoski, "(candidate last) hits high points with business crowd," <em>campaign &amp; elections</em>, 10/23/07) </p><p align="center"> <b>the (candidate last) vision: opening markets to help u.s. workers succeed</b> </p><p><b> <u>as president, gov. (candidate last) would open foreign markets and promote free trade:</u> </b> </p><p><b>gov. (candidate last) believes the united states must continue to work to open markets to american products.</b> "governor (candidate last) is a strong believer in free trade and opening foreign markets to american products. while continuing to promote free trade, governor (candidate last) will also work to ensure that free trade is fair and there is a level-playing field for american products." ((candidate last) for president, "the (candidate last) agenda: a conservative blueprint to strengthen the economy," press release, 10/9/07) </p><p><b>gov. (candidate last) proposes a new free trade zone of nations committed to high standards and enforcement.</b> "starting with a core of u.s. free trade agreement partners, governor (candidate last) would seek to bring together nations committed to open markets and playing by the rules in the largest ever free trade area, and go beyond traditional trade to promote high standards in areas critical to u.s. competitiveness. the reagan zone of economic freedom would act as an alliance working together internationally, in the world trade organization and elsewhere to push reforms and work cooperatively in areas like labor and the environment." ((candidate last)